### District Judge Kamala Ponnampalam:

1       This is an appeal against sentence filed by the Accused person Casper Ang (Hong Weiliang) (“the Accused”).

## Background

2       The Accused is a male, Singapore citizen, aged 34 years. At the time of the commission of the offences, the Accused was operating Singapore Funeral Supplies (“SFS”), a funeral services business registered in Singapore and having a company bank account with DBS.

3       The Accused faced a total of 28 charges for offences committed between November 2015 to February 2021. The charges involved a variety of offences. The Accused pleaded guilty to 11 charges and consented to have the remaining 17 charges taken into consideration for purposes of sentencing. The details of the charges and the sentences imposed are summarised in the table below.

#### Highlighted sentences were ordered to run consecutively

## The Facts[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

4       On 28 August 2018, First Data Merchant Solutions Pte Ltd (“First Data”) issued SFS with a card payment terminal to enable SFS to process card payments. First Data was in the business of providing cashless payment solutions for merchants in Singapore. These solutions included card payment terminals which enabled merchants to process card payments. Merchants could choose to have terminals which require the card to be physically present in order to process a transaction (“card present function”), or terminals which do not require the card to be physically present (“card not present function”). In the latter case, the merchant need only key in the card number and the expiry date to process the transaction. First Data issued SFS with a terminal with the card not present function. The terminal was at all times operated by the Accused.

#### Charges under Section 3(1) read with Section 10(1) Computer Misuse Act, Cap 50A (“the CMA offences”)

5       Between August 2018 and December 2018, the Accused used the terminal to process fictitious card transactions using card details of credit, debit or charge cards provided to him by his four co-conspirators, Wee Lian Heng Paul (“Paul”), individuals operating under the online personality named “TorCat”, individuals operating under the online personality named “Federation Russia” and “FiRuC”, and individuals operating under the online personality named “Libean”. The Accused processed the fictitious card transactions in an attempt to extract value from the cards provided to him. The Accused knew that his use of the terminal in this manner was not authorised by First Data.

6       The Accused also knew that that it was likely that the card details provided to him had been illegally obtained and that the charging of the cards was not authorised by the cardholders. He did not try to verify with the cardholders whether they had authorised the transactions. The Accused also did not know the true identities of TorCat, FiRuc or Libean, although he believed them to be Russian.

7       After a few transactions, the Accused started receiving “pick up card” messages for some unsuccessful transactions, which he knew indicated that the card had been stolen. He also received chargeback requests for some successful transactions, which he knew indicated that the card payments were not authorised by the cardholders. In total the Accused attempted to process 452 transactions. The transactions were either carried out pursuant to his conspiracies with his co-conspirators or on his own accord.

8       All the affected cardholders are believed to be foreign. 114 transactions with a total value of $356,600.80 were approved. 338 transactions with a total value of $1,403,139 were declined. Of the 114 approved transactions, 97 transactions with a total value of $330,539.80, were subsequently disputed by cardholders and made subject to chargeback. First Data received chargebacks from SFS’s transactions amounting to $335,989.60, which it has since refunded. First Data was unsuccessful in recovering these amounts from SFS directly, but it did set-off $54,635.94 from the funds otherwise payable to SFS. After deducting this amount from the amount in the 97 transactions which were made subject to chargeback i.e. $330,539.80, there was a net loss of $275,903.86 suffered by First Data as a result of the Accused’s scheme. The Accused earned at least $100,000 from his involvement in the scheme. No restitution has been made by the Accused.

#### Charge under Section 420 Penal Code, Cap 224 (“the cheating offence”)

9       The monies from the unauthorised transactions were credited to SFS’ bank account. The Accused devised a plan to obtain the monies from the account.

10     In or around 22 October 2018, the Accused’s sister-in-law and his wife had taken away his access to SFS’ finances, as they were concerned about SFS’ debt matters. The Accused’s sister-in-law took over custody of SFS’ chequebook. She insisted on copies of supplier invoices being shown to her before she released the blank cheques to the Accused for payments to the suppliers. The Accused decided to deceive his sister-in-law into releasing blank cheques to him, which he could then use to withdraw the monies credited into the account.

11     Between 25 October 2018 and 14 December 2018, the Accused submitted false invoices on a total of 13 occasions to his sister-in-law to deceive her into believing that funds were required to pay SFS’ suppliers. The invoices were falsified by the Accused. The Accused used the 13 cheques to withdraw a total of $265,110 from SFS’ bank account which he had identified as proceeds from the scheme.

#### Charges under Section 47(2)(b) and punishable under Section 47(6)(a) Corruption, Drug Trafficking And Other Serious Crimes (Confiscation Of Benefits) Act, Cap 65A (“the CDSA offences”)

12     Thereafter, the Accused regularly passed to Paul his share of the proceeds by way of cash or through bank transfer to Paul’s wife’s DBS bank account. In this way, the Accused transferred funds amounting to $9,895 on not less than seven occasions between 24 October 2018 and 30 November 2018.

13     For FiRuc, TorCat and Libean, the Accused made arrangements to meet up with persons acting on their behalf, to hand over their share of the criminal proceeds. The monies were then transferred onwards via Bitcoin. On some occasions, the Accused also transferred monies to FiRuc via Western Union to the name of Ekaterina Dryagina in Russia. Between 9 November 2018 and 22 November 2018, on at least four occasions, the Accused had transferred funds amounting to $22,750 to FiRuc.

#### Charges under Section 148(1) Companies Act, Cap 50 (“the bankruptcy offences”)

14     The Accused was made a bankrupt in 2014. He was made aware of his duties and responsibilities as a bankrupt. The Accused was aware that, as an undischarged bankrupt, he would need to seek permission from the Official Assignee (“OA”) or obtain leave of the High Court before he may be concerned in the management of a company.

15     Sometime in end-2018, the Accused registered the company Ang Brothers Funeral Services Pte Ltd in Singapore. As the Accused was an undischarged bankrupt, he enlisted a friend to act as the director and shareholder in name only. From about March 2019 to February 2020, the Accused was directly involved in the management of the company, managing the funeral services business of the company and overseeing the company’s operations throughout this period. The Accused did not have the written permission of the OA or the leave of the High Court to be involved in the management of the company.

16     Sometime in late 2019, the Accused met one Lim Chuan Kai Tommy (“Tommy”). In March 2020, they agreed to start a medical supplies business together. To this end, CT Care Express Pte Ltd (“CT Care”) was incorporated on 13 March 2020. Unbeknownst to Tommy, the Accused had asked his friend Sae Pang Yan Shuo (“Yan Shuo”) to lend his name for the incorporation of CT Care, as the Accused was still an undischarged bankrupt. Yan Shuo agreed, and CT Care was incorporated with Yan Shuo as its sole director.

17     Yan Shuo also opened a bank account for CT Care on the Accused’s instructions. He presigned the cheques for the account. Yan Shuo did not take part in the management of the company. From the date of CT Care’s incorporation to sometime in May 2020, the Accused was directly concerned in the management of CT Care, carrying out activities associated with the medical supplies business. The Accused as an undischarged bankrupt, did not have the written permission of the OA or the leave of the High Court to be involved in the management of the company.

#### Charge under Section 182 Penal Code, Cap 224 (“the offence of making a false police report”)

18     Tommy subsequently discovered that Yan Shuo was the sole director of CT Care and was not comfortable with this arrangement. On 4 July 2020, Tommy spoke to Yan Shuo and the Accused over the phone. Tommy explained that he needed Yan Shuo’s OTP to remove him as director. Yan Shuo provided his OTP over the phone, and Tommy removed him as director of CT Care. Subsequently, on 19 August 2020, the Accused lodged an online police report in Yan Shuo’s name, falsely alleging that Tommy had tricked Yan Shuo into handing over his Singpass by claiming that he wished to check on some secretariat details for CT Care. The report also falsely alleged that Tommy then used the OTP to remove Yan Shuo as director without Yan Shuo’s knowledge or consent. The Accused lodged the false report because he was unhappy that Tommy was taking away his control over CT Care and its bank account. The accused did not retract his false reports. Fortunately, the police did not pursue investigations against Tommy.

#### Charge under Section 468 Penal Code, Cap 224 (“the forgery offence)

19     On or about 12 August 2018, the Accused made an online application to American Express International, Inc (“AMEX”) for an American Express Krisflyer Ascend credit card. As he knew that an undischarged bankrupt would not be successful in such an application, the Accused made the application in the name of his father-in-law, Tan Hiong Eng (“Tan”). The Accused provided AMEX with Tan’s Notices of Assessment for Years 2017 and 2018, and a photocopy of Tan’s NRIC. The accused did not tell Tan that he was using Tan’s details for the application.

20     The accused completed the online application form with the intention of deceiving AMEX into believing that Tan had made the application, and thereby dishonestly inducing AMEX into delivering an American Express Krisflyer Ascend credit card to the Accused. The card was activated on 13 August 2018. Its credit limit was $3,000. Between 19 August 2018 and 28 December 2018, the Accused incurred expenses and charges on the credit card totalling $4,073.31. The Accused subsequently surrendered the card to his sister-in-law on or before 12 January 2019. The card was cancelled on 9 May 2019. There were no amounts outstanding on the card.

#### Charge under section 204A read with Section 511 Penal Code, Cap 224 (“the offence of attempted obstruction of the course of justice”)

21     On or about 21 April 2019, the Accused was arrested and detained at the Police Cantonment Complex’s Regional Lock-Up (“PCC RLU”). He was spotted in his cell by a police officer, Quak Tiong Beng (“Quak”), who held the rank of Staff Sergeant. Quak recognised the Accused from a previous encounter in 2017 when the Accused was detained for an unrelated case. Quak spoke with the Accused, who told Quak that he was under investigation.

22     On 23 April 2019, when Quak walked past the Accused’s cell, the Accused asked Quak to help him make a phone call to Yan Shuo. Quak agreed. The Accused told Quak to inform Yan Shuo that if an IO showed him a photograph, he was to tell the IO that he had seen the person in the photograph before but could not confirm who the person was. The Accused knew that the IO would interview Yan Shuo, and he wanted Yan Shuo to give a false account which was consistent with the Accused’s earlier lies to the police. The Accused did so intending to pervert the course of justice.

23     On the same day, Quak made the phone call to Yan Shuo. At the time, Yan Shuo was being interviewed by the IO. Yan Shuo had already been shown a photograph and he had said that he did not know the person and had not seen him before. When Yan Shuo received the call from Quak, he answered the call and put the phone on speaker mode in the presence of the IO. Quak then conveyed the Accused’s instructions to Yan Shuo. Investigations were subsequently commenced against Quak. Quak was charged with aiding the Accused to intentionally pervert the course of justice. He pleaded guilty to the single charge and was sentenced to five months’ imprisonment.

27     The Prosecution argued that the CMA offences entailed the systematic abuse of processing facilities for credit card transactions, resulting in credit card fraud in Singapore against foreign victims. The service provider incurred significant losses too. Such criminal activities undermine Singapore’s reputation as a financial and commercial hub. Singapore also bears the international responsibility to see that it does not afford a platform for the launch or the perpetration of this genre of fraud. A deterrent sentence is warranted in these circumstances.

28     The Prosecution further argued that the CMA offences are of the highest level of seriousness and merit the maximum sentence for each charge, having regard to the following offence-specific factors:

> a.     The harm caused was severe.

>> i.       Transactions worth S$356,600.80 were approved, of which chargebacks worth S$330,539.80 were received by First Data.

>> ii.       It may be inferred from the circumstances in which the credit card data was provided and the chargebacks which later occurred, that the vast majority of the credit card transactions were unauthorised by the cardholders.

>> iii.       First Data was unsuccessful in recovering their losses from SFS directly, and even after setting off sums otherwise owed to SFS, First Data was left with a loss of S$275,903.86 from these transactions. No restitution was made by the Accused.

> b.     The extent of the offending was significant. Having initially partnered with Paul, the Accused entered into separate arrangements with three online personalities (potentially part of a syndicate) to try out credit cards. In total, the accused attempted 452 transactions over a period of about two months.

> c.     The offences were planned and premeditated. The accused had to receive the credit card data and enter the transaction. If successful, he would then have had to withdraw the funds from SFS’s bank account, and then transfer his partners’ shares to them.

> d.     The Accused fully knew that his use of the card terminal in this manner was unauthorised by First Data and knew that it was likely that the transactions were not authorised by the cardholders. Despite receiving multiple chargebacks and “pick up card” notifications, he continued with the criminal scheme.

> e.     The accused was motivated by financial gain. He claims to have gained the substantial amount of about S$100,000 from the scheme. Based on his agreed share of profits, he would have earned even more.

29     The Prosecution reiterated that the Accused’s systematic abuse of credit card processing facilities cannot be condoned and must be strongly deterred. Notwithstanding his guilty plea, the CMA offences merit the maximum two years’ imprisonment per charge.

30     For the cheating offence, the Prosecution sought at least one year’s imprisonment for the following reasons:

> a.     The cheating offence was carried out by the Accused to enable him to withdraw his criminal proceeds from SFS’s bank account. This differs from the typical factual matrix where a cheating offence is committed in order to deceive a third party to give up property belonging to them and may be regarded as more analogous to a CDSA offence.

> b.     The offence-specific factors include the number of occasions of offending, the period of offending, the abuse of his sister-in-law’s trust, and the amount withdrawn. Further, it should be noted that the Accused is traced for property offences, although these are dated antecedents.

> c.     On balance and having regard to the precedents for s 47 CDSA offences, a sentence of at least one year’s imprisonment would be appropriate.

31     For the CDSA offences involving the transfer of the criminal proceeds from the scheme to his co-conspirators, the Prosecution pointed out that the Accused had transferred a total of $47,745. This amount includes the TIC charges. These offences enabled the Accused’s local and foreign conspirators to receive proceeds from the criminal scheme. Having regard to the amounts involved in the charges, and the sentencing precedents, the Prosecution submitted for at least one month’s imprisonment for DAC-911252-2020 and three months’ imprisonment for DAC-911253-2020.

32     For the forgery offence, the Prosecution argued that the predominant sentencing consideration is general deterrence. The forgery charge is a type of credit card fraud, namely application fraud, and attracts general deterrence. The offence is one of moderate seriousness based on the following offence-specific factors:

> a.     The Accused incurred expenses and charges totalling over $4,000. The expenses themselves were incurred between 19 August 2018 and 7 October 2018. That said, no loss was suffered by AMEX as the expenses incurred were fully paid.

> b.     The offence was premeditated. The Accused managed to obtain copies of Tan’s NRIC and Notices of Assessment and submitted those documents in support of the application.

> c.     There was an abuse of trust. The Accused used the identity of his own father-in-law to make the application.

> d.     The offence enabled the Accused to obtain credit when he was not supposed to as he was an undischarged bankrupt. Even if, as in the present case, there was no loss to the credit card company, the prevalence of fraud would lead to increased costs of credit for the community as a whole, due to the additional safeguards required to be taken.

33     The Accused is traced for property offences, although these are dated antecedents. The Prosecution submitted that having regard to the sentencing precedents, a sentence of at least five months’ imprisonment is appropriate.

34     For the bankruptcy offences, the Prosecution submitted for sentences of at least one month’s imprisonment for each charge. It was argued that the prohibition of an undischarged bankrupt from managing a company or business is intended to protect creditors’ interests and to prevent the misuse of the corporate structure for collateral purposes to the detriment of innocent third parties. If no harm were caused to anyone arising from the offence and there was no dishonest element in the commission of the offence, a fine would generally be sufficient. However, a custodial sentence would typically be appropriate if:

> a.     There was flagrant or reckless disregard of the prohibition;

> b.     The offence was committed over a prolonged period of time during which the offender was in active management; and/or

> c.     The offender has antecedents of the same or related offences.

35     In the case of the Accused, his bankruptcy offences crossed the custodial threshold, for the following reasons:

> a.     These were deliberate offences. The Accused knew that he needed to obtain permission or leave to be concerned in the management of the company. He flagrantly disregarded this legal requirement, when he registered Ang Brothers and later instigating Pang Shuo to register CT Care.

> b.     The extent of offending was significant. Including the TIC charges, the Accused was concerned in the management of five businesses, over a lengthy period of over four years. In relation to DAC-902299-2020, he was actively involved throughout.

> c.     In relation to the second offence in MCN-901553-2021:

>> i.       The offence was committed while the Accused was on bail, after he had been charged for the same offence.

>> ii.       The Accused asked Yan Shuo to incorporate the company, open a bank account and pre-sign cheques. This demonstrated some planning and premeditation, and was no doubt intended to conceal his involvement in the company from the authorities.

>> iii.       There was an element of abuse of trust, insofar as the Accused concealed the fact of his bankruptcy from his business partner.

36     In view of the factors above and the sentencing precedents, the Prosecution submitted that a custodial sentence was warranted for both charges and sought a sentence of at least one month’s imprisonment for each charge.

37     For the offence of making a false police report, the Prosecution submitted that whether the custodial threshold is crossed depends on the degree of harm caused or likely to be caused by the offence. If appreciable harm may be caused, a custodial term should be imposed as a starting point. The range of harm that may ensue includes loss of liberty (e.g. by causing another to be unjustifiably arrested) or harm arising from the wastage of public investigative resources. In the present case, the custodial threshold is crossed for the following reasons:

> a.     The report lodged by the Accused potentially disclosed cheating offences under s 417 PC. This is an arrestable offence and is punishable by imprisonment. While no harm in fact eventuated, Tommy could have been arrested and investigated.

> b.     The accused’s motive was malicious. He caused both reports to be lodged because he was unhappy with Tommy actions.

> c.     The offence was committed while the accused was on bail, for a similar offence under s 204A r/w s 511 PC. This demonstrates the accused’s recalcitrance and disregard for the law and calls for a sentence that reflects the need for specific deterrence.

38     In view of these factors and the sentencing precedents, it was submitted that a sentence of at least one month’s imprisonment would be appropriate.

39     For the offence of attempted obstruction of the course of justice, the Prosecution argued that general deterrence ought to be the primary sentencing consideration. Factors to be considered include:

> a.     The nature of the predicate charge;

> b.     The effect of the attempt to pervert the course of justice;

> c.     Whether the offence was committed to protect their own perceived interests; and

> d.     The degree of persistence, premeditation and sophistication in the commission of the offences.

40     In the present case, the offence was serious, having regard to the following offence specific factors.

> a.     The accused was being investigated for his misuse of the credit card terminal, which form the subject of the 1st to 10th and the 17th to 24th Charges. As discussed above, these are serious offences and are punishable by imprisonment.

> b.     The offence was committed to protect the accused’s own interests, and to bolster his lies to the Police that one “Boon Hien” was an accomplice in the predicate offences.

> c.     If the offence had been committed, further investigative resources could have been wasted in evaluating the accused’s claims. It is fortunate that the attempt failed as Yan Shuo happened to be in the course of a police interview when Quak called him.

41     Quak was charged with aiding the accused to intentionally pervert the course of justice. He pleaded guilty to the single charge on 8 June 2021 and was sentenced to five months’ imprisonment. As Quak was a police officer and had breached his duty, these are factors which would have prompted a need for a heightened sentence on the grounds of deterrence. However, the Accused remains the primary offender and stood to benefit from the perversion of the course of justice. Having regard to the circumstances of the case, Quak’s sentence and the sentencing precedents, The Prosecution argued for a similar sentence of at least four months’ imprisonment.

42     The Prosecution urged the Court to run six sentences of imprisonment consecutively. These are reflected in the table above. The Prosecution concluded that a sentence of at least 4 years 11 months’ imprisonment is proportionate to the totality of the accused’s offending, gives adequate weight to the accused’s guilty plea, and is not a crushing term of imprisonment.

## Mitigation Plea[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)

43     The mitigation plea set out the Accused’s personal circumstances and recorded his remorse for his foolish actions. He is married with two teenaged sons who are schooling. He is the sole-breadwinner, and other than his immediate family, he also supports his elderly parents. He is presently self-employed and runs a funeral service. His company has carried out several outreach programs and provided free funeral services for families in need. He was recently diagnosed with diffuse fatty infiltration of the liver following chest pains. It was stated that a long incarceration would cause hardship to his family.

44     The mitigation plea also responded to the Prosecution’s sentencing submissions. There was no disagreement in general with the Prosecution’s sentencing position save for the sentences for the CMA offences. The Defence argued that the CMA offences did not warrant the maximum punishment. A term of 18 to 20 months’ imprisonment, with two of the sentences running consecutively, would be fair in view of the Accused’s plea of guilt. The offences, while they are serious, are not so exceptionally serious that they merit the maximum punishment. Neither do the circumstances of the offence reveal that the Accused will not be deterred by anything less than the maximum sentence. The Defence cited the case of _Angliss Singapore Pte Ltd v Public Prosecutor__[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4)_ for the principle that general deterrence per se is not a reason for imposing the maximum sentence.

45     It was further argued that the maximum sentence is typically reserved for the worst type of cases caught by the provision. The Defence cited the following cases to demonstrate that only offences involving the loss of life, racial hostilities, or corruption involving millions of dollars, merit the maximum sentence.

> a.      _Public Prosecutor v Govindasamy s/o Nallaiah__[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)_– involving the offence of culpable homicide not amounting to murder;

> b.      _Koh Lee Beng v Public Prosecutor__[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6)_ – involving the offence of grievous hurt motivated by racial hostility;

> c.      _Public Prosecutor v Fazely bin Rahmat__[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)_ - involving the offence of grievous hurt resulting in death; and

> d.      _Public Prosecutor v Choy Hon Tim_ (unreported) (DAC 18908/1995) – involving the offence of corruption with bribes amounting to $13 million.

46     The present case did not involve the same degree of harm or the high level of culpability which warrants the maximum sentences. Such a sentence would be crushing to the Accused person.

## Decision on Sentence

### Areas of dispute and agreement

47     The sole area of dispute between parties centred around Prosecution’s submissions for the maximum sentence for the three proceeded charges for the the CMA offences. The offence is punishable with imprisonment not exceeding two years and/or a fine of up to $5,000. The Prosecution argued that the nature of the offences and the manner of the offending reflected a high degree of culpability and when added to the serious harm or loss suffered by the victim, First Data, the offences warranted the maximum punishment of two years’ imprisonment per charge. The Prosecution further submitted that the sentences for two of the CMA offences ought to run consecutively.

48     The Defence countered that the maximum punishment for any offence must be reserved for the worst type of cases dealt by the court which was not the case here. The Defence submitted for a sentence of between 18 to 20 months’ imprisonment for each of the CMA offences. The Defence did not object to sentences in two of the charges to run consecutively.

49     With regard to the other offences, there was no apparent disagreement between the Prosecution and the Defence on the sentences sought by the Prosecution. The Defence made no submission on sentence for the other offences and did not appear to dispute any of the arguments which the Prosecution made in support of the sentences sought for those other offences. I will nevertheless address the submissions made for all the offences.

### Sentencing Approach for the CMA offences

50     The Prosecution cited two sentencing precedents for the CMA offences.

51     In _Public Prosecutor v Leong Kiat Hoe__[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8)_, the offender was charged with a single CMA offence. He was a bartender at a nightclub and had entered into a conspiracy with three others to commit the CMA offence. The offender and his colleague took photographs of customers’ credit cards which were sent to one Koh, knowing that the information would be used to perform unauthorised monetary transactions. The offender sent photographs of five credit cards to Koh. In return, the offender was paid $250, of which he gave $50 to his colleague. Three of the credit cards were used to make EZ-Link top-ups amounting to $8,500. No restitution was made. The offender was untraced. He was sentenced to five months’ imprisonment.

52     In _Public Prosecutor v Ashlyn Keara Ho Foong Mun__[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)_, the offender was charged with inter alia, 10 CMA offences. The offender took her romantic partner’s ATM card and used it to make 10 unauthorised transfers to her bank account totaling $46,000. The transfers involved two amounts of $3,000 and eight amounts of $5,000. The offender was untraced and had made full restitution. She was sentenced to two 2 months’ imprisonment for the transfers involving $3,000 and 3 months’ imprisonment for the transfers involving $5,000. She was given a global sentence of 13 months’ imprisonment, including five months’ imprisonment for the CMA offences.

53     I agreed with the Prosecution, and the Defence conceded too, that the facts in the present case are far more egregious than those of the precedent cases, and a substantial uplift in sentence is justified. There were a total of 452 transactions attempted, of which 114 transactions were successful. Subsequently, 97 of these transactions were disputed by the cardholders and made subject to chargebacks. First Data made refunds on all the disputed transactions which amounted to $335,989.60. Part of this loss was borne by SFS when First Data set off an amount of $54,635,94 due and payable to SFS. The remaining loss amounting to $275,903.86 was borne entirely by First Data. The figures are unprecedented and indeed staggering.

54     The Accused earned a sum of $100,00 for his involvement in the CMA offences. This is significantly higher than the amounts earned by the offenders in the precedent cases, but unlike those offenders who repaid in full, the Accused made no restitution.

55     The present case also involves a greater level of sophistication, with an international element. All the cardholders were believed to be foreign and three of the Accused’s co-conspirators, TorCat, FiRuc and Libean, were likely foreign too. The Accused believed them to be of Russian origin. The Prosecution correctly pointed out that the criminal scheme entailed the systematic abuse of processing facilities for credit card transactions, resulting in credit card fraud against foreign victims and losses to the service provider. Such criminal activities undermine Singapore’s reputation as a financial and commercial hub.

56     In _Angliss Singapore Pte Ltd v Public Prosecutor_, the High Court made the following observations:

> _It is trite law that “the maximum sentence should be reserved for the worst type of cases falling within the prohibition”: see Sim Gek Yong at \[12\]–\[13\]. By imposing a sentence close to or fixed at the statutory maximum, a court calibrates the offender’s conduct as among the worst conceivable for that offence. In other words, when Parliament sets a statutory maximum, it signals the gravity with which the public, through Parliament, views that particular offence: Cheong Siat Fong v PP_ _<span class="citation">\[2005\] SGHC 176</span> at \[23\]; R v H (1980) 3 A Crim R 53 at 65._

57     I agreed with the Defence that while the CMA offences committed by the Accused were serious, the harm or losses caused were not the worst of its type. The amounts lost did not run into the millions and the harm caused was not so severe as to be akin to the loss of a life. Likewise, the Accused’s conduct in this criminal enterprise was not such that it can be characterised as the _worst conceivable_ for the offence. It is not inconceivable that there could be a worse CMA offence involving multiple merchants like SFS and several different service providers like First Data, which would likely result in far higher losses. A criminal scheme like that would warrant the maximum sentence.

58     While I took the view that the CMA offences did not merit the maximum sentence, given the many offence-specific factors and the extent of the offending behaviour as highlighted by the Prosecution, a sentence close to the maximum prescribed was necessary to have the desired deterrent effect. The total sentence must also reflect the gravity of the offences. Accordingly, I imposed a sentence of 20 months’ imprisonment for each charge and ordered two of the sentences to run consecutively.

### Sentencing Approach for the cheating offence

59     The Prosecution submitted that the cheating offence was atypical of the usual cheating offences and was somewhat analogous to a CDSA offence. The Accused had perpetrated the deception to gain access to the monies which were the fruits of the CMA offences. I accepted the analogy and relied on the case precedents cited for the CDSA offences. At the same time, I made reference to the leading case of _Public Prosecutor v Fernando Payagala Waduge Malitha Kumar_ (“the _Payagala_ case”)[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) for the sentencing range recommended by the High Court for a cheating offence. Admittedly, the _Payagala_ case was concerned with credit card cheating. Nevertheless, given the fact that the present cheating offence sprung from offences related to the misuse of credit cards, I found that the general sentencing considerations such as (a) planning and premeditation, (b) sophistication of the offence including measures taken to avoid detection, (c) role of the accused, (d) the number of offences and quantum involved, (e) the extent of actual loss, damage and adverse consequences (both tangible and intangible) to victims and connected parties, (f) the international dimension, and (g) any remorse shown by the accused,[^11] to be relevant and applicable.

60     In _Public Prosecutor v Ho Man Yuk and ors_,[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12) the three offenders discovered a glitch in gaming machines at Marina Bay Sands Casino. By exploiting this glitch, they were able to obtain Free Play Credits which they used for games at various electronic roulette machines. They encashed S$875,133.56 in winnings from the Free Play Credits. They remitted some of the criminal proceeds overseas, converted some into casino chips, and transferred some. The three offenders were convicted for criminal misappropriation and CDSA offences after trial. In sentencing, the trial judge applied the following sentencing bands to the CDSA offences.

> a.     For amounts from $5,000 to less than $10,000 – 1 month’s imprisonment.

> b.     For amounts from $10,000 to less than $40,000 – 2-4 months’ imprisonment.

61     In _Chong Kum Heng v Public Prosecutor__[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13)_, the offender was charged for CBT offences as well as CDSA offences. The offender was a project manager employed by an engineering company which was in the business of carrying out electrical and cabling works. The project managers of the company were permitted to sell the excess cables as scrap and use the sale proceeds for site expenses and/or personal usage and out of pocket expenses and staff incentives. The offender sold the wastage for two building projects and deposited a total of S$214,000 into his bank accounts. He made withdrawals for the purchase of a condominium unit, a car and insurance and also to pay for his credit card charges. Of these withdrawals, a total of S$153,300 represented his criminal proceeds. The offender made no restitution and none of the proceeds were recovered. The offender claimed trial and at first instance, he was sentenced to 39 months’ imprisonment. On appeal, the global sentence was reduced to 32 months’ imprisonment. The High Court refined the sentencing bands applied by the District Judge in _Public Prosecutor v Ho Man Yuk and ors_ and set out the following broad sentencing bands for CDSA offences[^14].

> a.     For amounts less than $5,000 – three weeks’ imprisonment.

> b.     For amounts from $5,000 to less than $10,000 – three weeks’ to two months’ imprisonment.

> c.     For amounts from $10,000 to less than $40,000 – two to six months’ imprisonment.

62     In the _Payagala_ case, the offender misappropriated a credit card belonging to a passenger seated next to him on a flight. When he arrived in Singapore, he used the credit card to make a number of expensive purchases at the airport terminal. He was arrested at the airport and the purchases were seized. He was charged for criminal misappropriation of the credit card and cheating. The High Court set out the following starting point for credit card cheating offences.

> a.     Syndicated and/or counterfeit/forged credit card and/or sophisticated offences – 24 to 36 months’ imprisonment for each charge.

> b.     Non-syndicated stolen/misappropriated credit card offences – 12 to 18 months’ imprisonment for each charge.

63     According to the CDSA precedents, for amounts above $40,000, the sentence should be higher than six months’ imprisonment. In the _Payagala_ case, for non-syndicated stolen or misappropriated credit card offences, the starting point of 12 months’ imprisonment was deemed appropriate. In the present case, there is no direct evidence of syndicate involvement. I viewed this offence as a non-syndicated one. Given the large amount of $265,110 involved, the flagrant abuse of his sister-in-law’s trust, and having regard to the precedent cases for the CDSA offences, I agreed with the Prosecution that a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment would be appropriate for the cheating offence.

### Sentencing Approach for the CDSA offences

64     The sentencing bands (referred to above) and the individual sentences imposed by the High Court in the case of _Chong Kum Heng v Public Prosecutor_ were instructive. The offender had claimed trial to all the charges. For the CDSA offences, the individual sentences imposed were as follows:[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15)

> a.     five months’ imprisonment for offence involving $30,000;

> b.     five months’ imprisonment for offence involving $29,000;

> c.     six months’ imprisonment for offence involving $40,000;

> d.     two months’ imprisonment for offence involving $9,000;

> e.     four months’ imprisonment for offence involving $25,300; and

> f.     four months’ imprisonment for offence involving $20,000.

65     The Accused pleaded guilty to two CDSA offences and consented to have a further two CDSA offences taken into consideration for purposes of sentencing. The amounts involved in the proceeded charges were $9,895 and $22,750. Based on the sentences imposed in _Chong Kum Heng v Public Prosecutor_, the two charges would attract two months’ and four months’ imprisonment, respectively. I agreed with the Prosecution that given that the Accused has pleaded guilty, a downward adjustment is justified. The Accused was sentenced to one month’s imprisonment and three months’ imprisonment respectively for the two proceeded charges.

### Sentencing Approach for the forgery offence

66     The prescribed punishment for the forgery offence is imprisonment of up to 10 years, and also be liable to a fine. The Prosecution submitted for a sentence of five months’ imprisonment and cited two case precedents in support.

67     In _Public Prosecutor v Chew Kong Heng__[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)_, the offender was convicted after trial to two forgery offences. The offender had signed application forms for two credit cards in the name of one Lee, without Lee’s consent. The loss that flowed from the offences was $1,970 and $9,593.63. The offender was untraced and no restitution appeared to have been made. The offender was sentenced to eight months and 14 months’ imprisonment respectively for the two charges. The appeal against conviction was dismissed and the sentences were not varied on appeal.

68     In _Public Prosecutor v Ashlyn Keara Ho Foong Mun_, the offender pleaded guilty to two forgery offences amongst others. The offender applied for two credit cards in her girlfriend Denise’s name, signing off on the application form as Denise. She also provided supporting documents for the application namely, copies of Denise’s NRIC and IRAS Notices of Assessment. Denise did not know or consent to this. Both applications were approved. The offender then used the credit cards to make various purchases, resulting in sums of $5,827.25 and $10,717.21 being owed to the respective banks. The offender made full restitution. She was untraced. She was sentenced to five months’ imprisonment for each of the forgery offences. Her appeal against sentence was dismissed.

69     The facts in the present case are similar to that in the precedent cases. The amount here is $4,073.31, is comparable the amount for one of the charges in _Public Prosecutor v Ashlyn Keara Ho Foong Mun_ - $5,827.25. The Accused has pleaded guilty and there were no amounts owing and due to the credit card company. On the other hand, I acknowledge and agree with the Prosecution’s submissions that the offence was one of moderate seriousness involving the abuse of the Accused’s father-in-law’s trust. Credit card fraud of this nature will have consequences for the community as a whole with a possible rise in the cost of credit. There is also the added aggravating factor that the Accused was an undischarged bankrupt when he committed these offences. All considered, I agreed with the Prosecution that a sentence of five months’ imprisonment should be imposed for this forgery offence. This sentence was ordered to run consecutively.

### Sentencing Approach for the bankruptcy offences

70     The Accused pleaded guilty to two bankruptcy offences and consented to have two other similar charges to be taken into consideration for purposes of sentencing. The bankruptcy offence is punishable with a is fine not exceeding S$10,000 or imprisonment of up to two years or both. The issue here is whether the custodial threshold is crossed on the facts of this case. The Prosecution argued for one month’s imprisonment for each charge and cited two sentencing precedents.

71     In _Yap Guat Beng v Public Prosecutor__[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)_, the offender pleaded guilty to one bankruptcy offence and two similar offences were taken into consideration. The offender had acted as a director of a company while she was an undischarged bankrupt. She faced other charges for taking part in the management of a business while being an undischarged bankrupt. She was sentenced to six weeks’ imprisonment for the bankruptcy offence. Her appeal against the custodial sentence imposed was allowed. The sentence was reduced to a fine of $7,000 in default four weeks’ imprisonment. The High Court held that there were no aggravating factors which warranted the imposition of a custodial sentence. No loss had been suffered as a result of the offender’s offences. There was no basis to find that the accused was dishonest. Her involvement in the company began before she was declared a bankrupt and ceased soon after she was informed of the prohibitions by the Official Assignee. Her last act of management took place only about a month after she was notified of the same.

72     In _Public Prosecutor v Lee Chuin Khuen__[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)_, the offender pleaded guilty to three charges under Section 417 Penal Code, Cap 224, and one charge for taking part in the management of a sole proprietorship under Section 26(1) Business Registration Act, Cap 32. Four bankruptcy offences amongst other charges were taken into consideration for the purposes of sentencing. Briefly, the offender, who was an undischarged bankrupt, took part in the management of a sole proprietorship and also operated two other companies. The offender was aware of the prohibitions and had deliberately taken steps to circumvent them by using other persons to register the business and the companies. The unlawful management by the offender had resulted in losses to innocent third parties and the District Judge found that the offender had the intention to defraud them. The offender was also traced for bankruptcy offences. He was sentenced to three months’ imprisonment for the offence under Section 26(1) Business Registration Act. The offender’s appeal against sentence was withdrawn.

73     I accepted the Prosecution’s submission that the first precedent case can be distinguished from the present case. The Accused here registered both companies, Ang Brothers and CT Cares, after he was declared a bankrupt. He had operated the companies over a longer period. The second precedent case, whilst being similar to the present case, was more aggravated. The offender faced more charges for managing a business whilst still an undischarged bankrupt. He also had similar antecedents. Hence a downward adjustment to the custodial term is warranted.

74     I agreed with the Prosecution that these were deliberate offences and there was flagrant or reckless disregard of the prohibition. The extent of offending was significant. The Accused was concerned in the management of five businesses, over a lengthy period of over four years. A further aggravating factor is that the later offence was committed while the Accused was on bail after he had been charged for the earlier offence. The Accused took active steps conceal his involvement in the company from the authorities. He recruited Yan Shuo to incorporate the company, open a bank account and pre-sign cheques. He had also abused his business partner’s trust.

75     In view of these aggravating factors, I accepted the Prosecution’s submissions that the custodial threshold had been crossed and imposed a sentence of one month’s imprisonment for each charge. The sentence for one charge was ordered to run consecutively.

### Sentencing Approach for the offence of making a false police report

76     This offence is punishable with imprisonment for up to two years and/or a fine. The issue here again is whether the custodial threshold is crossed. In the case of _Public Prosecutor v Koh Yong Chiah__[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)_, the 3-Judge Panel of the High Court held that whether the custodial threshold is crossed should essentially be determined based on the degree of harm caused or likely to be caused by the offence. This refers to both actual and potential harm. It was stated that if appreciable harm might be caused by the offence, the courts should, as a starting point, impose a custodial term. The court qualified that 1) the harm must be causally connected to the provision of false information, and 2) the harm in question must be more than de minimis. The Court further stated that the duration that the falsehood was maintained would usually be a relevant factor to assess the potential harm caused by the offence. This determination of the appropriate starting point is the first step of the test.

77     The second step is to consider other relevant sentencing factors to take into account the level of culpability of the offender and to determine if the starting point should be departed from and what would be the appropriate quantum of fine or length of imprisonment. The High Court observed that where the offender falsely reported innocent persons to the Police, imprisonment terms tend to be the norm.

78     In the present case, I agreed with the Prosecution that the Accused’s acts were motivated by malice. He filed the reports because he was unhappy about Tommy’s actions. The report lodged disclosed a serious offence - cheating under Section 417 Penal Code, Cap 224. This is an arrestable offence and is punishable by imprisonment. The Accused did not retract his report. The false report was filed while the Accused was on bail, for a similar offence under Section 204A Penal Code. The police did not investigate Tommy and while no harm was actuated by the false report, there was the real risk of Tommy being arrested and investigated.

79     On the balance, given the Accused’s recalcitrance and disregard for the law, I saw no reason to depart from the sentencing norm of a custodial sentence. I accepted the Prosecution’s submissions and imposed a term of one month’s imprisonment. This sentence was ordered to run consecutively.

### Sentencing Approach for the offence of attempted obstruction of the course of justice

80     The prescribed punishment for this offence is imprisonment for up to 7 years and/or fine. The Prosecution submitted for a sentence of at least four months’ imprisonment and cited two case precedents in support.

81     In _Public Prosecutor v Sy Yong Da__[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)_, the offender pleaded guilty to one charge for the offence of attempted obstruction of the course of justice, amongst others. This was a fatal hit-and-run accident. The offender was the driver of a car and had operated the vehicle whilst under the influence of alcohol. He was also feeling very tired and sleepy and was speeding. He lost control of the vehicle, mounted the kerb and collided into a pedestrian. He drove off from the scene without stopping to render assistance. Neither did he report the collision. The pedestrian subsequently died from the injuries sustained. Immediately after the collision, the offender sent his vehicle to the workshop for repairs. The court in imposing a sentence of four months’ imprisonment observed that the offence here was serious. The offender’s plan to cover up his involvement was elaborate. The offender had his vehicle immediately towed to the workshop for repairs and waited at the workshop until it opened for business. He was later identified through quick police investigations and eye-witnesses accounts.

82     In _Public Prosecutor v Yeo Jiawei__[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)_, the offender was investigated for cheating and money laundering activities in which the offender had acted as an intermediary. The offender attempted to intentionally pervert the course of justice by doing the following: 1) Asking one Samuel and one Kevin to lie to the police that monies transferred by Samuel were Samuel’s investments; and 2) Asking one Jose to dispose of his laptop which would likely contain relevant evidence and not to travel to Singapore to avoid being interviewed by the police. The offender had also abetted one Jose to intentionally pervert the course of justice by instigating Jose to tell Aloysius to lie to the police that he did not know of certain of the offender’s dealings if questioned. The offender was sentenced to 15 months’ imprisonment for the attempted offence and seven months’ imprisonment for the abetted offence.

83     I accepted the Prosecution’s submissions that in terms of the level of culpability, the Accused’s offending behaviour is comparable to that of the offender in _Public Prosecutor v Sy Yong Da_. The Accused was being investigated for his misuse of the credit card terminal which is the predicate offence and a serious one. The offence of attempted obstruction of the course of justice was committed to protect the Accused’s own interests, and to bolster his lies to the Police. It was fortunate that the attempt failed. Otherwise, further investigative resources would have been expended. Quak who had pleaded guilty to a single charge was sentenced to five months’ imprisonment. He was deserving of a higher sentence as he had breached his duty as a police officer. Nonetheless, the Accused was the primary offender and I agreed with the Prosecution that a sentence of four months’ imprisonment would be appropriate. The sentence was ordered to run consecutively.

### Total Sentence

84     The Prosecution submitted for a global sentence of four years’ and 11 months’ imprisonment. The Defence appeared to be seeking a sentence of not more than four years’ and three months’ imprisonment. Having taken into account the Accused’s plea of guilt, the number of charges involved, the period of offending and the huge losses suffered by the victims, and after taking a last look at the individual sentences, I was satisfied that the individual sentences imposed which culminate in a global sentence of 51 months’ imprisonment is just and appropriate. Each individual sentence is adequate to address the separate legal interests involved but did not add up to a global sentence which was crushing. Further orders were made take into account the periods when the Accused was in remand and to exclude the periods when he was on bail.

## Conclusion

85     The sentences imposed were neither crushing nor manifestly excessive. They adequately address the sentencing objectives of this case.
